# Security

<name> is a self-hosted, single-household app. It runs on a home Pi behind
oauth2-proxy forward-auth and a reverse proxy (Traefik) — it is **not** a
public, multi-tenant service. The threat model is: <state it in one or two
sentences — what must stay isolated, and surviving an honest operator
misconfiguration without silently leaking secrets>.

## Trust boundaries

- **Edge auth (forward-auth).** The app sits behind oauth2-proxy; it trusts
  `X-Auth-Request-User` / `X-Auth-Request-Email` only because Traefik strips
  any client-supplied copy before forwarding. The app validates the headers are
  present (401 if not), never logs them (PII), and runs no own login/session in
  this mode. <If anonymous access is allowed, say so + what's gated.>

- **CSP / response headers.** <The CSP the backend sets (see rust-axum) — what's
  allowed to load, why any `unsafe-*` is present, frame-ancestors, etc.>

- **Per-user / per-resource isolation.** <If the app holds per-user data, how
  every query is scoped; if single-user, say there's no multi-tenant model.>

- **Inter-service auth.** <Each loopback sidecar/worker: the bearer token it
  requires (constant-time compare), and that loopback bind is the primary
  control. Delete if single-binary.>

- **Outbound fetches / filesystem.** <Any upstream the app calls (host
  allowlist, verified TLS, size caps) and any path built from external input
  (sanitized before hitting the filesystem; no `..` escape). Delete if none.>

## Secrets

All secrets are injected at runtime via env (never baked into images or
committed): <list them, e.g. `<NAME>_TOKEN`, sidecar tokens>. The `.env.example`
files hold placeholders only; `.env`, `*.db*`, and any credential/data dirs are
gitignored. Containers run as a non-root UID.

